  <h2>Phonological Inventory Comparison</h2>

  <p>The phonological systems of Brazilian and European Portuguese share core segments but exhibit important differences in realization and distribution.</p>

  <h3>Vowel Systems</h3>

  <p>Both variants possess the same underlying vowel inventory: seven oral vowels (/i, e, ɛ, a, ɔ, o, u/) and five nasal vowels (/ĩ, ẽ, ɐ̃, õ, ũ/). However, surface realization differs dramatically due to European Portuguese's extensive vowel reduction in unstressed syllables.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Phoneme</th>
        <th>Brazilian Realization</th>
        <th>European Realization</th>
        <th>Environment</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>/a/ (unstressed)</td>
        <td>[a] or [ɐ]</td>
        <td>[ɐ] or [ə]</td>
        <td>Pretonic, final</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>/e/ (unstressed)</td>
        <td>[e] or [i]</td>
        <td>[ɨ] or deleted</td>
        <td>Pretonic</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>/o/ (unstressed)</td>
        <td>[o] or [u]</td>
        <td>[u] or deleted</td>
        <td>Pretonic</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>/ɛ, ɔ/ (stressed)</td>
        <td>Open vowels maintained</td>
        <td>May raise in certain contexts</td>
        <td>Stressed position</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>/ẽ, ɐ̃/ (nasal)</td>
        <td>Distinct qualities</td>
        <td>May merge in some contexts</td>
        <td>Before consonants</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Consonant Realizations</h3>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Phoneme</th>
        <th>Brazilian Realization</th>
        <th>European Realization</th>
        <th>Environment</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>/s/ (final/coda)</td>
        <td>[s] or [z] (voicing)</td>
        <td>[ʃ] (palatalization)</td>
        <td>Word-final, before consonants</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>/z/ (intervocalic)</td>
        <td>[z]</td>
        <td>[ʒ] (palatalization)</td>
        <td>Between vowels</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>/ʁ/</td>
        <td>[ʀ], [χ], [h], [ɾ]</td>
        <td>[ʀ], [ʁ]</td>
        <td>All positions</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>/t/ + /i/</td>
        <td>[tʃ] (palatalization)</td>
        <td>[ti] (no palatalization)</td>
        <td>Before unstressed /i/</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>/d/ + /i/</td>
        <td>[dʒ] (palatalization)</td>
        <td>[di] (no palatalization)</td>
        <td>Before unstressed /i/</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>/l/ (final)</td>
        <td>[w] or [u] (vocalization)</td>
        <td>[ɫ] (velarization)</td>
        <td>Word-final</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>/ʎ/</td>
        <td>[ʎ] or [j] (merger)</td>
        <td>[ʎ] (maintained)</td>
        <td>All positions</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Register Classification System</h2>

  <p>The following framework classifies registers and formality levels across variants, supporting appropriate language selection for different contexts.</p>

  <h3>Formality Levels</h3>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Level</th>
        <th>Brazilian Features</th>
        <th>European Features</th>
        <th>Typical Contexts</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Intimate</td>
        <td>Você; informal vocabulary; contractions</td>
        <td>Tu; highly reduced speech</td>
        <td>Family, close friends</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Casual</td>
        <td>Você; colloquialisms; slang</td>
        <td>Tu/Você depending on age; colloquial</td>
        <td>Friends, social media</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Neutral</td>
        <td>Você; standard vocabulary</td>
        <td>Você; moderate reduction</td>
        <td>General conversation</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Formal</td>
        <td>Você; careful articulation; avoidance of slang</td>
        <td>O senhor/a senhora; conservative grammar</td>
        <td>Business, education</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Ceremonial</td>
        <td>Formal address; elaborate constructions</td>
        <td>Third-person address; archaisms</td>
        <td>Official ceremonies, academic</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Conclusion</h2>

  <p>This knowledge base provides the structured reference materials necessary for serious engagement with Portuguese variant studies. As the language continues evolving—trends we explore in our <a href="/portuguese-variants/trends/">Current Trends & Future Outlook</a> section—these ontological frameworks require ongoing refinement and expansion.</p>

  <p>Users should supplement this reference material with practical application through our <a href="/portuguese-variants/tools/">interactive tools</a> and awareness of common <a href="/portuguese-variants/challenges/">communication challenges</a>. The intersection of systematic knowledge and practical skill ultimately enables effective navigation between Portuguese variants in any context.</p>
